## Architecture

{% if architecture == "layered" %}
Layered architecture (`controller / service / repository / dto / entity / exception`):

```
src/main/java/{{ package_path }}/
├── controller/    # REST controllers
├── service/       # Business logic
├── repository/    # Spring Data JPA repositories
├── dto/           # Request / response DTOs (incl. ApiResponse<T>)
├── entity/        # JPA entities
└── exception/     # GlobalExceptionHandler + custom exceptions
```

A sample CRUD slice (`SampleEntity` → `SampleRepository` → `SampleService` → `SampleController`)
demonstrates the layering end-to-end. Replace it with your own domain.
{% elif architecture == "hexagonal" %}
Hexagonal / ports-and-adapters architecture:

```
src/main/java/{{ package_path }}/
├── domain/                  # Pure domain: model + ports
│   ├── model/               # Domain entities (no framework annotations)
│   └── port/
│       ├── in/              # Inbound ports (use cases)
│       └── out/             # Outbound ports (driven by adapters)
├── application/             # Use-case implementations
└── adapter/
    ├── in/web/              # Driving adapter: REST controllers
    └── out/persistence/     # Driven adapter: JPA persistence
```

The domain layer has zero framework dependencies. Adapters wire it to Spring.
{% else %}
The default Spring Boot layout is used (single root package). Consider adding an architecture
skeleton with `springup add architecture layered|hexagonal` (future).
{% endif %}

